---
description: Java and Spring Boot best practices — layering, transactions, entity design, REST, and general code quality. Apply to all Java source files.
globs: **/*.java
---

## Layering
- Controllers delegate to services — no business logic in controllers
- Services delegate to repositories — no query construction in services
- Entities never leak into the controller layer — always map to a DTO or record before returning
- No `@Autowired` on fields — use constructor injection only

## Transactions
- `@Transactional` belongs on service methods, not repositories or controllers
- Never wrap an external HTTP call (OpenAI, REST client, messaging) inside a `@Transactional` method
- Specify `readOnly = true` on read-only service methods
- Avoid `@Transactional` on `private` methods — Spring AOP cannot proxy them

## Entity and ORM design
- Fetch strategy must be explicit on every `@OneToMany` and `@ManyToOne` — no implicit EAGER
- Every `@OneToMany` collection must have an index on the foreign key column
- Use `@EntityGraph` or `JOIN FETCH` for queries that need associated data — avoid N+1
- Bidirectional relationships must have a helper method to keep both sides in sync
- Entities must not implement `Serializable` unless there is a clear reason
- `equals()` and `hashCode()` on entities must be based on a natural business key, not the generated ID
- Never expose mutable entity collections directly — return unmodifiable views or copy to a new list

## Repositories
- Use Spring Data derived query methods for simple queries
- Use `@Query` with JPQL for anything complex — fall back to native SQL only when JPQL is insufficient and document why
- Never build query strings by concatenating user input

## REST API
- Use `@RestController` + `@RequestMapping` — never mix `@Controller` and manual `@ResponseBody`
- Validate all request bodies with `@Valid` and JSR-380 annotations on the DTO/record
- Use `@ControllerAdvice` + `@ExceptionHandler` for all error responses — no raw exceptions to the client
- Return `ProblemDetail` (RFC 9457) for error responses — consistent structure across all endpoints
- Use `ResponseEntity<Void>` for 204 No Content — do not return `null`

## Code quality
- No method longer than 30 lines — extract to a private method or a collaborator
- No magic numbers or strings — use named constants or enums
- Logging must use parameterized SLF4J form: `log.info("id={}", id)` not string concatenation
- No `System.out.println`, `e.printStackTrace()`, or raw `java.util.logging`
- No commented-out code in committed files
- `Optional` must not be used as a method parameter or field — only as a return type
